 Evoker<Br>
 The Circle of Eternity<BR>
 <a href="mailto:tegellan@hotmail.com">tegellan@hotmail.com</a><BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ufyo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fyo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(7/9/01 6:45:34 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Spankda Updage -- Level 45</span><hr size=1> First off, I love your updates Spankda.  These and Bic's guide last week finally convinced me to start quadding at level 36.  I started out with the single and double pulls in OT, but promptly moved to EW after reading Bic's guide and haven't looked back.  I've since reached 39 and have taken a break to enjoy my new-found mobility and work on some tradeskills.  So, thanks to both of you guys for your assistance and information; it's been most helpful.<br>
<br>
Now, for some questions on things that you mentioned in your post.<br>
<br>
1 - When can I go to CS to dump my tusks and how should I go about this?  I've heard it's very difficult.  My bank is filling up with them but I want to cash them in for gems rather than sell them.<br>
<br>
2 - How did you get dubious with Cov?<br>
<br>
Zralgon Zimmers <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uspankda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Spankda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(7/9/01 7:13:56 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Skyshrine and CS</span><hr size=1> Thanks for the encouraging words foks!<br>
<br>
Okay, some words on getting to Cobalt Scar.<br>
<br>
First, the pathway is from EW *through* Kael Drakkel to Wakening Lands to Skyshrine.<br>
<br>
In Skyshrine, you need a key to get to Cobalt Scar.  Ideally, you /ooc in the zone and some nice people group with you and take you.<br>
<br>
I did exactly that except I got my own key.  You get the key to Skyshrine in one of two ways:  Kill Zilgark Whisperwing or do his quest.<br>
<br>
I chose the death route.  It wasn't easy.  I got lucky and a couple of guild mates just happened to be in the zone and helped me.  Whisperwing is level 25 and not a problem to kill.  It's the guardians nearby that are the problem.  He drops the Skyshrine key.<br>
<br>
Okay.  You either have the key or you are grouped with someone with the key.  You go to this big room with a dragon statue in it in the middle of the room.  Take out the key and put it on your cursor.  Click the key on the statue.  You're now in Cobalt Scar.<br>
<br>
Getting through Kael is tricky.  Get a good map.  You will need to be invisible throughout the Kael journey.  It's very scary.  I've done it twice and both times were tense.  <br>
<br>
In WL, remain invisible and get the key to the WL dragon circle.  This way, if anything bad happens, you can always port back and not have to pass through Kael again.  <br>
<br>
Beware Woushi.  Some report he sees invis.  Some say he doesn't.  In all liklihood, Woushi will occassionally self-buff with see invis.<br>
<br>
Run along the zone line to Skyshrine.<br>
<br>
Get a good map of Skyshrine and go to the dragon statue.<br>
<br>
Get a good map of Cobalt Scar.  The tooth-key is on a big boulder in the middle of the dragon circle.  Remain invis if you're KOS to CoV.<br>
<br>
Once you have the CS tooth, you can destroy the GD and WL teeth.  This is Verant's way of making the number of soul-bound items below eight.  I only have the CS tooth and I port to GD and WL all the time.<br>
<br>
I did all of this by myself with just maps from eqmaps.com and the key that I got by killing Whisperwing with help.<br>
<br>
Cov Faction:  I got down to dubious by killing lots and lots and lots and lots of giants in GD.  Basically, by the time you are WARMLY with the Coldain, you are likely to be dubious with CoV.  For sure, by the time you're ALLY with the Coldain, you'll be Dubious with CoV. <br>
<br>
Note the only way to check your faction with CoV is to go to Skyshrine and /con the guards while not invisible.  You will not be able to shop in Skyshrine until you're better than dubious.  I'm not sure if Apprehensive is good enough.<br>
<br>
Wyverns in CS are on the CoV faction but killing them does *NOT* lower your CoV faction.  So, while they won't agro on me, I can kill them with impunity.<br>
<br>
I'm able to bank in Skyshrine with Dubious faction.<br>
<br>
The Skyshrine key is also soulbound.  I now have two soulbound items in my inventory:  CS tooth and Skyshrine key.<br>
<br>
Once you have the CS tooth you can theoretically destroy the Skyshrine key.  I'm keeping mine because I can now lead groups through to CS.  Likewise, I often zone into SS to heal up.  Then, I use the key to zone back into CS to hunt Wyverns.<br>
<br>
The safest place to meditate and go AFK is in the tower in CS that leads to SS.  However, there is a possibility of someone training Bulthar or Sirens up there and zoning themselves and leaving you to take the brunt of the beatings. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uamankhann45.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Amankhann45</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(7/9/01 9:47:31 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Skyshrine and CS</span><hr size=1> Wow, thanks for all the great information, Spankda!  And glad to hear you're doing well with the quadding!<br>
<br>
One question for you - Where can I find a good map of Kael?  EQAtlas doesn't have one up yet.  Do you know of any other places to check?  EQMaps is now charging for access, and I'd rather avoid that site if at all possible.<br>
<br>
Thanks!<br>
<br>
Amankhann <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cova69>Cova69</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(7/9/01 11:35:00 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Spankda Updage -- Level 45</span><hr size=1> A few extra notes to append to this, as I recently finished up the same few lvl's (48 as of last night).<br>
<br>
Only time I ever saw a shardwurm in GD, it handed my ass to me on a plate.  I don't know which ones are/aren't casters (or what type I had, someone trained it on me, it was blue so I tried to kite it), and I have horrible resists.  I couldn't get a nuke through it's faster-casting, interrupting nukes.  At 20% HP I hadn't hit it yet, so I ran outta range and gated out.<br>
<br>
The Ulthork warriors in EW are still blue at 47 (haven't looked at 48, I think they still are though), but I have to spend so much time killing greens to get enough of them that it's not worth the time to do them for exp.  I still find myself back there now and then for the tusks though.  I was quadding for exp here starting at around 41 (wish I had started sooner), and could quad the warriors then (200 int, maybe 30 or 40 in +mana).<br>
<br>
Walruses are just zone garbage for me now, but the wolly rhino's are blue, and not bad exp.  I quadded them a bit at lvl 45/46, but they don't stay together at the end.  Usually most of them would go to run mode at the same time, and I'd just root the one/two that would still follow me, and then nuke/harvest/med them to death one at a time.  If one falls out of the pack early, loop back with triple, root the single one and come back to it later after another AE on whats left.  This is also not bad if you have a partner.  There was a 35 druid here quadding walruses when I was doing the rhino's.  If he got an add he couldn't handle, or was oom at the end I'd drop and AE to finish them.  And when I was oom, he'd drop a nuke on the one or 2 rooted rhino's still left.  We were both getting solo exp, but it was safer and easier for both of us.<br>
<br>
I've been doing the wyverns in CS a bit now.  Compared to quadding the exp is quite slow (full bar of mana to kill one blue, or full bar to kill 4 blues, easy math), but is also easier and safer I find.  Being KOS to CoV I kite up and down the beach (othmir love me because of the ulthork quadding).  Lev and invis and run up the hill to find a nice target (and make sure no drakes are near), run off cliff and when a bit away hit the flux staff.  Easy going from there, I've never had a problem with getting an add.  I can't wait for 51, when I get a spell capable of quadding them with.  I think your estimation of their HP is a bit off though, I find them to be more in the range of 3500 to 4000 HP.  (stuff in the 2500 to 3000 range is what I look for to quad)  Also, they don't gate back to spawn point - they warp when they hit run mode.  If you watch their HP carefully and don't run out of spell range when they get low, I find they don't warp.<br>
<br>
Also, I haven't seen it mentioned anywhere here before, but I found quadding sarnak knights in OT to be great exp from 45 to 48 (as in good in 47 to get to 48, I think they may be too green now, may have to single-kite for a few lvl's as I can't find anything good now).  Seeing as they seem a relatively new idea around here, I'll put up a quick guide about how I do it.<br>
<br>
Note:  this may be dangerous if you are KOS to the goons, I am not.  But if you are careful you shouldn't have any problems.<br>
<br>
Starting at the SF zone/ramp (where I med up between pulls), run down to the road, and turn right - towards FM.  Follow the road down the bottom of that valley, pulling any sarnaks that are blue that you see along the way with the staff/something else.  Don't use snare to pull though, or it'll be broken by the time you get 4.  Chickens and cactuses run the same speed as the sarnaks if you want to include them in the pull, but they will drop out of the quad at low HP, and you have to kill them singly afterwards.  Tigers and rhino's are faster (tigers I can barely outrun with jboots, rhino's kick my butt to the zone), avoid aggro'ing them while pulling at all costs.  The path I follow while looking/pulling continues down the road (bottom of that valley, watching both hillsides) to just past the crossroad in front of FM.  Then I turn left (into the zone) over a little hill and the sarnak fort/ruin should be in front of you.  Run past this but leave some clearance, you don't want to pull anything from inside the ruin, though there are wonderers around the outside of it sometimes to grab.  Turning left more there is a large plain on the back-side of the hill that formed the valley of the road.  Following the back-side of this hill around (again, you will be in a small valley, watch both sides for sarnaks) you will come back to the small yellow lake in front of SF.  A quick loop around that lake and by then I usually have my 4 victims.  I usually like to pull them over the hill towards the outpost, and kill them in the large flat area there (hills mess with spell range I find) though sometimes I turn towards SF and kite around that lake.<br>
<br>
There are a couple things to be careful of when doing this.<br>
<br>
1. Rhino's will ruin your day, stay away from them.  If you get one and are close to the zone, zone.  If you don't have any sarnaks mad at you yet, stop and root it, then you can step back, snare, and single-kite as usual.  If you already have a train you'll have to take beats from the rhino (they don't bash at least, never been stunned by it and had the train catch me too) till you get far enuf from the train to stop and root the rhino.  Then you can pull the train off and quad them far away while the rhino forgets about you.  Zone to clear aggro completly before starting another quad though.<br>
<br>
2.  Sometimes sarnaks will have SoW.  If you get a SoW'd one in your group, treat it like a rhino.  But you can prevent SoW'd sarnaks from wandering the zone.  Head to that fort near FM, and one at a time slaughter ever caster in there.  If you invis, scout it out, and target the caster, then run out of spell range, and slowly get closer 1 step at a time so you are at max range you can cast on it through the wall and he won't bring any friends from inside with him (95% of the time).  I usually root him through the wall from max range, then procede to nuke him to death.  Often they don't break root before they are dead.  If they do I can get them re-rooted before they get to me, then snare them out there (don't want to use the AE on them when they are near friends, might hit extra's) and kite as usual.  Keep slaughtering casters till melee's take the spawns, and then don't pull from inside there anymore.  Casters only spawn as statics, and I only quad wanderers.  Usually takes me 1/2 an hour to an hour to clear the casters, and then I can quad for hours and hours and not see a single SoW'd sarnak.<br>
<br>
3. Goons.  If you're KOS, pretty self explanetory.  If you're not, stay away from them anyways.  They will latch onto your quad, and the last thing you want is to catch him in your AE.  I was so incredibly close to doing that once that I stay as far away from them as possible now.  I would have died there, but the goon happened to be on the sarnak I had targeted, and just before I cast the spell he killed the knight, and I got a &quot;you must have a target&quot; message instead of a mad goon.<br>
<br>
4. The large plain out by the fort, but back farther towards the pit where HS is.  Scorpicus's there are on VS faction (same as goons), so they don't bother me.  But there are tunnels under the plain there and I've caught ones that I can't see underground in AE's before.  Being harm-touched by something you can't see through 500 feet of rock really sucks.<br>
<br>
It can be dangerous at times (more so than quadding other things, say ulthorks), but I went through lvl 45 in record time (less than 10 hours of play time, prolly closer to 5 to 7 hours), and 46 and 47 were cake too (about 1/2 green at 47, though still giving exp.  Haven't tried at 48, though I expect them to be too green to be worth it.)<br>
